2500|$|Double-positive thymocytes (CD4+/CD8+) move {{deep into}} the thymic cortex, where they are {{presented}} with self-antigens. [...] These self-antigens are expressed by thymic cortical epithelial cells on MHC molecules {{on the surface of}} cortical epithelial cells. [...] Only those thymocytes that interact with MHC-I or MHC-II appropriately (i.e., not too strongly or too weakly) will receive a vital [...] "survival signal". All that cannot (i.e., if they do not interact strongly enough, or if they bind too strongly) will die by [...] "death by neglect" [...] (no <b>survival</b> <b>signal).</b> [...] This process ensures that the selected T-cells will have an MHC affinity that can serve useful functions in the body (i.e., the cells must be able to interact with MHC and peptide complexes to effect immune responses). [...] The vast majority of all thymocytes end up dying during this process.|$|E
